,"id":"44553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44800"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70927"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of painless swelling of his face, neck and arms. He also reports a bluish discolouration on his chest. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is facial plethora (not pictured) with his trunk examination as seen (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary valvular incompetence","Subclavian vein thrombosis","Cirrhosis","Vasculitis","Superior vena cava syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior vena cava syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. The superior vena cava (SVC) is a large vein that carries deoxygenated blood from the upper half of the body back to the right atrium. SVC syndrome occurs when there is partial or complete obstruction of blood flow through the SVC, leading to the characteristic symptoms and signs including swelling of the face and upper limbs, distended neck and chest wall veins, and cyanosis of the face, neck and upper torso. It is most commonly due to external compression by a mediastinal mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary valvular incompetence\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes chronic venous insufficiency in the lower limbs and would not explain the upper body distribution of symptoms or the acute presentation in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubclavian vein thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause unilateral arm swelling and pain but would not cause bilateral upper limb swelling, facial swelling or cyanosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause peripheral oedema and venous distension but typically affects the lower body first and would be accompanied by other signs of liver disease such as ascites and spider naevi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E affecting large vessels could theoretically cause some vascular compromise but would not typically present with this pattern of venous obstruction and would usually be accompanied by systemic symptoms such as fever and weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common causes of SVC syndrome are lung cancer and lymphoma, particularly in older patients with a smoking history. Given this patient\u0027s age, smoking history, and clinical presentation, the most likely underlying cause is lung cancer. Further investigations, particularly a CT chest with contrast, would be necessary to confirm the diagnosis and identify the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Superior vena cava syndrome is characterised by facial and upper limb swelling, distended neck and chest wall veins, and cyanosis of the face, neck and upper torso.","Lung cancer and lymphoma are the most common causes of superior vena cava syndrome.","CT chest with contrast is the diagnostic modality of choice for superior vena cava syndrome."],"references":["Azizi, A, Shafi, I, Shah, N. et al. Superior Vena Cava Syndrome. J Am Coll Cardiol Intv. 2020 Dec, 13 (24) 2896\u20132910. Available at: https://www.jacc.org/doi/10.1016/j.jcin.2020.08.038","Trivedi SB, Ray C, Chadalavada S, Makramalla A, Kord A. Superior Vena Cava Syndrome: An Update and Literature Review of Percutaneous Endovascular Treatments. Semin Intervent Radiol. 2022 Nov 17;39(4):446-453. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9671675/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56393"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13809"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20752"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20752"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aRTMHdNcQOzG9gMbiJ0H9bx02oFBEE.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aRTMHdNcQOzG9gMbiJ0H9bx02oFBEE.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56393"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T15:20:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T15:36:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6426"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70927"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"creat